    <p class="text-gray-300">The S key schedules use the round function to generate round keys <em>k<sup>i</sup></em> . Let <em>K</em> be a key for a S2<em>n</em> block cipher. We can write <em>K</em> = (<code>&lt;em&gt;m&lt;/em&gt;−2, . . . , </code>0, <em>k</em>0), where <code>&lt;em&gt;i&lt;/em&gt; , &lt;em&gt;k&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt; ∈ GF(2)&lt;em&gt;&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/em&gt; , for a value of &lt;em&gt;m&lt;/em&gt; in {2, 3, 4}. Sequences &lt;em&gt;k&lt;sup&gt;i&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/em&gt; and </code><em><sup>i</sup></em> are defined by</p>

